2500|$|In 2002, former US President, Bill Clinton {{described}} Kashmir as [...] "the {{most dangerous}} {{place in the}} world." [...] He averted a nuclear war between India and Pakistan {{over the issue of}} Kashmir according to former US Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott. Talbott reveals in his book Engaging India: Diplomacy, Democracy and the Bomb that India and Pakistan came very close to a nuclear war in 1999. [...] According to Talbott, before Clinton met with Prime Minister of Pakistan, Nawaz Sharif in 1999 to discuss the issue, US national security adviser <b>Sandy</b> <b>Berger</b> told Clinton that he could be heading into [...] "the single most important meeting with a foreign leader of his entire presidency".|$|E
