5000|$|Critics claim many {{inaccuracies}} in the film, {{including the}} depiction of the Clinton administration. For example in one scene, former National Security Advisor <b>Sandy</b> <b>Berger</b> is portrayed as unwilling to approve a plan {{to take out a}} surrounded Osama bin Laden. He leaves it to former CIA Director George Tenet to decide if he will take responsibility. In the original version of the film, Berger hangs up the phone on Tenet, and Tenet calls off the operation. No reliable verification of this event has ever been discovered. In fact, even Richard Miniter [...] - [...] a conservative author and critic of the Clinton administration [...] - [...] was quoted as saying [...] "The idea that someone had bin Laden in his sights in 1998 or any other time and <b>Sandy</b> <b>Berger</b> refused to pull the trigger, there’s zero factual basis for that." ...|$|E
